{{Infobox film | name = This River | film name = | image = | caption = | director = {{Plainlist| * [[Katherena Vermette]] * Erika MacPherson}} | producer = Alicia Smith | writer = {{Plainlist| * Katherena Vermette * Erika MacPherson}} | starring = Kyle Kematch | music = | cinematography = Iris Ng | editing = Erika MacPherson | studio = [[National Film Board]] | distributor = | released = 2016 | runtime = 18 minutes | country = Canada | language = English | budget = }}
'''''This River''''' is a 2016 Canadian short documentary film directed by [[Katherena Vermette]] and Erika MacPherson.<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/indigenous/new-documentary-shows-lengths-taken-to-find-missing-1.3746810 "New documentary shows lengths taken to find missing family members"]. [[CBC News]], September 4, 2016.</ref> The film centres on Drag the Red, a volunteer group in [[Manitoba]] who search the [[Red River of the North|Red River]] for the bodies of [[Missing and Murdered Indigenous Women]].<ref>[http://muskratmagazine.com/this-river-documentary-searches-for-missing-and-murdered-indigenous-women-girls/ "This River Documentary Searches for Missing and Murdered Indigenous Women & Girls"]. ''Muskrat'', August 4, 2016.</ref>
Smith has stated that it was Vermette's ''North End Love Songs'' which helped draw her attention to the perspectives of indigenous youth from the North End and the experience of having missing family members.<ref name="Larkins">{{cite news|last1=Larkins|first1=David|title=New doc explores search for missing people|url=http://www.winnipegsun.com/2016/11/06/new-doc-explores-search-for-missing-people|accessdate=8 November 2016|work=Winnipeg Sun|date=6 November 2016}}</ref>
Principal photography took place August 8 to 16, 2016, with an all-woman crew documenting the work of Drag the Red volunteer Kyle Kematch. The crew spent much of that time filming from a small fleet of donated boats. The director of photographer was Iris Ng, with Anita Lubosh recording sound.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://blog.nfb.ca/blog/2015/10/02/redemption-red-river-woman/|title=Redemption on the Red|last=Lewis|first=Philip|date=2015-10-02|work=NFB/blog|access-date=2017-06-09|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=en-US}}</ref>
The film received the 2016 Coup de coeur du jury award at Montreal's [[Terres en vues/Land InSights]] First Peoples' Festival and had its public premiere in Vermette's hometown of [[Winnipeg]] on October 5 at the [[Winnipeg Art Gallery]].<ref name="King">{{cite news|url=http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/arts-and-life/entertainment/arts/local-film-about-tragic-red-river-searches-honoured-at-montreal-festival-389664751.html|title=Local film about tragic Red River searches honoured at Montreal festival|last=King|first=Randall|date=9 August 2016|work=[[Winnipeg Free Press]]|accessdate=11 August 2016}}</ref> At the [[5th Canadian Screen Awards]] in 2017, the film won the [[Canadian Screen Award]] for Best Short Documentary Film.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Carter|first1=Sue|title=Katherena Vermette doc This River wins Canadian Screen Award|url=http://www.quillandquire.com/awards/2017/03/13/katherena-vermette-doc-this-river-wins-canadian-screen-award/|accessdate=9 June 2017|work=Quill and Quire|date=13 March 2017}}</ref>
==''What Brings Us Here''== Vermette and producer Alicia Smith also created a related [[Instagram]] work, ''What Brings Us Here'', which offers portraits of volunteers behind the community-run Winnipeg search teams the Bear Clan and Drag the Red.<ref name="Cram">{{cite news|last1=Cram|first1=Stephanie|title=Instagram project asks what attracts volunteers to patrol Winnipeg neighbourhoods|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/indigenous/instagram-project-asks-what-attracts-volunteers-to-patrol-winnipeg-1.3824950|accessdate=8 November 2016|publisher=[[CBC News]]|date=29 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Chua|first1=June|title=Instagram project chronicles search for missing and murdered Indigenous women|url=http://rabble.ca/columnists/2016/11/instagram-project-chronicles-search-missing-and-murdered-indigenous-women|accessdate=9 June 2017|work=rabble.ca|date=10 November 2016|language=en}}</ref>
''What Brings Us Here'' features photos by Winnipeg photographers Janine Kropla, Mark Reimer and Karen Asher. The online work combines images of searchers with their statements about why they are continuing to look for loved ones—and answers.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Botelho-Urbanski|first1=Jessica|title=Instagram storytelling explains why Winnipeggers pitch in to find missing persons|url=http://www.metronews.ca/news/winnipeg/2016/11/02/instagram-storytelling-explains-pitching-in-to-find-missing-pers.html|accessdate=9 June 2017|work=Metro Winnipeg|date=2 November 2016|language=en}}</ref>
